Run the model on a NeuronCore via **`torch-neuronx` (XLA)** in `torch.bfloat16`. There is **no eager mode** on Neuron — compile the forward with `torch_neuronx.trace` / `bucket_model_trace` at fixed shapes and call the compiled module per request (`torch_xla` placement under the hood). Do NOT run inference on CPU or in `float32` — it will be far too slow, and a CPU fallback is incorrect for this target. The first `neuronx-cc` compile of each new graph shape takes minutes, so keep shapes **static** (fixed prompt/decode buckets), pre-compile buckets at startup, and reuse the persistent compile cache so later steps hit it instead of recompiling. For a fast decode you **may use NxD Inference** (`neuronx_distributed_inference`) — its `KVCacheManager` + `ModelBuilder` give a **device-resident, in-place KV cache** (raw `torch_neuronx.trace` cannot keep KV resident, so passing the cache through the graph boundary every token is host-bound and slow). Using NxD's KV-cache / tracing utilities is allowed here; just keep the model's own layers yours. **Flash attention is available on Trainium too** (the NKI kernel `nki_flash_attn_func`) — it is *not* NVIDIA-only; prefer it over a naive `softmax(QK^T)V` to cut the attention activation peak. See the `neuron-pytorch`, `nxd-kv-cache`, and `neuron-flash-attention` serving-systems references.
